There are several ways a web application can communicate between two browser tabs:

1. **Window.postMessage()**: This method allows you to send a message from one window to another. You can use it to send data between tabs by getting a reference to the other window and calling postMessage() on it.

   ```javascript
// In the sending tab
var otherTab = window.open('https://example.com');
otherTab.postMessage('Hello', 'https://example.com');

// In the receiving tab
window.addEventListener('message', function(event) {
    if (event.origin === 'https://example.com') {
        console.log(event.data); // prints "Hello"
    }
});
```

2. **SharedWorker**: SharedWorkers are used to share data between windows. They are created in one window and can be accessed from all other windows in the same origin.

   ```javascript
// In the sending tab
var worker = new SharedWorker('shared-worker.js');
worker.port.postMessage('Hello');

// In shared-worker.js
self.addEventListener('message', function(event) {
    self.clients.matchAll().then(function(clients) {
        clients.forEach(function(client) {
            client.postMessage('Hello back');
        });
    });
});
```

